        "text[TOK_Q_DELIM]For individuals over 50, the grid rules acknowledge that it's harder to adapt to new occupations due to age-related limitations. For instance, a person who has performed light work for the past fifteen years and is now limited to seated work is considered disabled at age 50, provided they don't have skills that transfer to seated jobs. At age 55, the rules further relax, considering individuals who have done medium exertional work but are now limited to light work as disabled, even if they might physically perform other lighter exertion jobs. This illustrates the importance of age in disability determination under the grid rules.[TOK_Q_DELIM]Answer": {
